CHILE DAYBOOK: Central Bank Discloses Minutes From Rate Meeting

-- B y   R a n d y   W o o d s
-- 
2011-05-27T04:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-27/chile-daybook-central-bank-discloses-minutes-from-rate-meeting.html
Chile ’s central bank will release
minutes of its last monetary policy meeting on the bank’s
website at 8:30 a.m. New York time.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*Codelco, the world’s biggest copper company, will disclose
first-quarter results simultaneously on the regulator’s website
and in a presentation by Chief Executive Officer  Diego Hernandez 
at the company’s headquarters at 1 p.m. New York time.  EQUITIES:
*The Ipsa index increased 0.8 percent to 4,839.87.
*Cencosud SA, Latin America’s third-largest retailer by sales,
gained 1.8 percent to 3,598.7 pesos. Consumer stocks rose after
a report showed Santiago retail sales increased 15.2 percent in
April from a year earlier.
*Lan Airlines SA advanced 0.8 percent, the most in two weeks, to
13,586 pesos.  Latin America ’s largest airline by market value
rose the day of a public hearing at Chile’s antitrust tribunal
to discuss its planned takeover of  Brazil ’s Tam SA.
*Socovesa SA fell the most in six weeks, retreating 2.6 percent
to 312.67 pesos. The real-estate developer posted a first-
quarter net loss of 1.92 billion pesos, after a profit of 154
million pesos a year earlier.  MARKETS:
*Euroclear Bank SA,  Europe ’s largest settlement agency, will
start operating in Chile next month, Finance Minister Felipe Larrain told reporters in a conference call from Paris.
*Euroclear could help make the peso more international, the
minister said. The peso strengthened 0.4 percent to 469.48 per
U.S. dollar and has gained 15 percent in the past year.
*The central bank sold five- and 10-year inflation-adjusted
bonds at yields of 2.64 percent and 2.92 percent, respectively,
according to data posted on the bank’s website.
*The bank paid an average of 469.99 per  U.S. dollar  for $50
million yesterday, according to data published on its website.
It’s buying $12 billion to limit the peso’s gain.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
